[2] New Zealand (Dunedin, Otago)
Date: Thu 17 Aug 2017 19:45 NZST
Source: Stuff [edited]
http://tinyurl.com/y7a56fv5


University of Otago students are being offered free booster shots after about 10 confirmed or suspected cases were reported in Dunedin [Otago, South Island].

Three young people in Marlborough have contracted the contagious illness, with at least 1 case linked to an Auckland outbreak, while 2 have been confirmed in Nelson.

Nationally, an unusually high number of cases were reported from September 2016 to early 2017, and the Ministry of Health warned of "an increased risk of further outbreaks".

Auckland reported 51 cases of mumps in the past month -- most aged 10 to 19 -- while several were recorded in Waikato earlier this year [2017].

The Auckland Regional Public Health Service said last month [July 2017] it was concerned not enough people were immunised in the face of the mumps outbreak.

The MMR vaccine is usually given in 2 doses, one at 15 months old and one at 4 years old.

Most people recover from mumps, but it can have serious complications. The disease can cause inflammation of tissue surrounding the brain (meningitis), inflamed testicles or ovaries and deafness.

Men hospitalised from the Auckland outbreak had pain and swelling in their testicles, known as orchitis, which in rare cases may lead to infertility.

The outbreak in Dunedin has prompted the Otago tertiary institution's student health team to offer free measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) booster shots to students who have not had two MMR vaccinations since 1990, or are unsure of their vaccination history.

Pro-vice-chancellor of health sciences Professor Peter Crampton, the convener of the university's pandemic planning group, said the group was "determining our ongoing response as the situation develops."

The outbreak coincided with a large-scale boil water notice issued for parts of Dunedin, including the student quarter, after untreated water got into part of the town's drinking water supply on [Mon 14 Aug 2017].

All students and staff had been sent information about mumps. Information had been posted on social media.

Marlborough medical officer of health Dr Andrew Lindsay said mumps is "highly contagious". It spreads through the air by breathing, coughing and sneezing, or through contact with infected saliva; by kissing or sharing food and drink. It usually takes 12-25 days before symptoms appear -- including pain in the jaw, fever, headache, and swollen glands around the face and body. People with mumps re infectious for 7 days before swelling starts and for 5 days after they cease.

Personal hygiene is essential to avoid catching mumps, including frequent hand washing, stopping coughs and sneezes in tissues, keeping at least 1 metre [3 ft] away from others and ensuring kitchens and bathrooms are clean.

Dr Jill Sherwood, public health physician with the ESR (the Institute of Environmental Science and Research), earlier said the MMR vaccine was not as effective in mumps as it was in measles and rubella. "The mumps component is only about 85 per cent effective, whereas the measles component will most likely give you lifetime coverage," Sherwood said.

There have been no reported cases of mumps in Canterbury, a health board spokeswoman said.

[Byline: Hamish Mcneilly, Jennifer Eder]

